ameMeanings":[{"name":"Murdac","type":"LAST","attribution":"Dictionary of Family Names in Britain and Ireland © University of the West of England 2016","meanings":["Irish, Scottish:  see  Murdoch  ."],"variants":[{"name":"Murdoch","meanings":["Scottish: from an Anglicized form of the Gaelic personal names <i>Muireadhach</i> ‘mariner’, <i>Murchadh</i> ‘sea-warrior’, and <i>Muircheartach</i> ‘sea-ruler’, the first element in each being <i>muir</i> ‘sea’. The personal name was introduced into Yorkshire and Normandy by Norsemen from Ireland as early as the 10th century. The surname in post-Conquest medieval England usually belongs to Norman families."]}]},{"name":"William","type":"FIRST","attribution":"Dictionary of First Names © Patrick Hanks and Flavia Hodges 1990, 2003, 2006.","meanings":["Probably the most successful of all the Old French names of Germanic origin that were introduced to England by the Normans. It is derived from Germanic <i>wil</i> ‘will, desire’ + <i>helm</i> ‘helmet, protection’. The fact that it was borne by the Conqueror himself does not seem to have inhibited its favour with the ‘conquered’ population: in the first century after the Conquest it was the commonest male name of all, and not only among the Normans. In the later Middle Ages it was overtaken by   John  , but continued to run second to that name until the 20th century, when the picture became more fragmented."],"variants":[]}],"lifeSummary":"William Murdac was born in 1240, in Leicestershire, England, United Kingdom as the son of Henry Murdac and Unknown. He married Isolda of Leicestershire about 1264, in Leicester, Leicestershire, England. They were the parents of at least 1 daughter. He died after 1267, in his hometown."},"et":{"1240–Aft 1267":"1240–pärast 1267","1240–1267":"1240–1267","1244–1267":"1244–1267","1266–1326":"1266–1326","1220–1279":"1220–1279","–Female":"Surnud","1326":"1326","1279":"1279","1267":"1267","1266":"1266","1244":"1244","Aft 1267":"pärast 1267","1220":"1220",